@SELF: Node Alpha (GPT4o)  
@GOAL: Determine the type of chemical bond formed between sodium and chlorine in NaCl.  
@INT: Analyze the nature of the interaction between sodium (Na) and chlorine (Cl) atoms.  

Sodium (Na) is an alkali metal with one electron in its outer shell, which it tends to lose to achieve a stable electron configuration. Chlorine (Cl) is a halogen with seven electrons in its outer shell, needing one more to complete its octet. When sodium transfers its outer electron to chlorine, both achieve stable electron configurations. This electron transfer creates a positively charged sodium ion (Na⁺) and a negatively charged chloride ion (Cl⁻). The electrostatic attraction between these oppositely charged ions forms an ionic bond.

@C: High confidence in this analysis due to well-established chemical principles regarding electron transfer and ionic bond formation.

Initial Answer: B) Ionic bond

